<subSubSection id="D518776A0E4A70C68FF390E445BD3694" pageId="10" pageNumber="45" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="CF4874ECDA73E7F65AF59911670D8942" pageId="10" pageNumber="45">
<pageBreakToken id="A2D728CB7A94A43E915569E330E43754" pageId="10" pageNumber="45" start="start">Diagnosis</pageBreakToken>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="04F8AB36B27B83A44AED28A63BC9B7F8" pageId="10" pageNumber="45">
Similar to 
<taxonomicName id="247FC3C8CB4F2C0EB16D871E8A9D65EA" class="Liliopsida" family="Commelinaceae" genus="Murdannia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Murdannia paraguayensis" order="Commelinales" pageId="10" pageNumber="45" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="paraguayensis">
<emphasis id="EF0032CD7DCA5EA9B7E117C918AA3CEC" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="45">Murdannia paraguayensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
due to its deflexed pedicels at post-anthesis and when fruiting; petals with minute glandular hairs at base on the adaxial surface; filaments, ovaries, styles and capsules with minute glandular hairs, and capitate stigma. It can be differentiated by its trailing stems, distichously-alternate leaves, inflorescence reduced to a solitary cincinnus, peduncles with a mixture of eglandular and glandular hairs, cincinni 2-7-flowered, capsules broadly ovoid to broadly ellipsoid, and 1-seeded locules.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
